### Variables and Data Types

Any data a program uses must be stored in main memory locations, each given its own identifier while the program runs. Values in these locations may change — this is why they are called variables.

Each variable has:

- identifier: a unique name that refers to a memory location
- data type: defines the type of data stored and the operations that can be performed on it

---

### Data Types

| Data Type      | Type of Data                                               | Typical Memory |
|----------------|-------------------------------------------------------------|----------------|
| integer        | A whole number, e.g. 3, 45, -453                           | 2 or 4 bytes   |
| real/float     | A number with a fractional part, e.g. 34.456, -9.234, 4.0 | 4 or 8 bytes   |
| char/character | A single character — any letter, digit, punctuation or symbol | 1 byte       |
| string         | Zero or more characters — null, one character, or many     | 1 byte per character |
| Boolean        | True or False only                                         | 1 byte         |

Note: Different programming languages may use different names (e.g. "real" is called "float" in some languages) and different amounts of memory.

---

### Declaring Variables

In some languages, variables are declared at the start of a program so the appropriate memory can be reserved. Example in Visual Basic:

```
dim num1 as integer
dim total as single
dim choice as char
dim username as string
dim found as Boolean
```

In Python, variables are not declared — the language infers the data type from the value assigned:

- a = 23 → integer
- b = "Fred" → string

---

### Assignment Statements

Values are assigned to variables using =:

```
x = 1
pi = 3.242
alpha = "a"
street = "Elm Street"
over18 = True
```

---

### Constants

A constant is a value that remains the same throughout the program. It is given a unique identifier and declared at the start.

Declaration example:

```
CONST VAT_RATE = 0.2;
```

Usage later in code:

```
sellPrice = netPrice * VAT_RATE + netPrice;
```

Two benefits of using constants:

- If the value changes, you only need to update it in one place
- Code is easier to read and understand — the identifier is used instead of a number, making it easier to debug and maintain

In Python there is no special constant declaration — use an uppercase identifier by convention to signal it should not be changed:

```
VAT_RATE = 0.2
```

---

### Input and Output Statements

Example 1 — input a name and display a greeting:

```
myName = input("Please enter your name: ")
print("Hello ", myName)
```

- The input statement displays the prompt on screen and waits for the user to enter a value
- The value entered is assigned to myName
- The print statement outputs: Hello John (if John was entered)

Alternative two-statement form:

```
print("Please enter your name: ")
myName = input()
```

One combined statement is preferred in most algorithms.

