### Misconceptions

- misconception: Variables and constants are the same thing
  reality: Variables can change value during program execution. Constants are set once and should not change. Using a constant makes code safer and easier to maintain.
  trigger: When students use a variable where a constant would be more appropriate, or vice versa
  correction_prompt: If a value should never change during the program (e.g. VAT rate, PI), declare it as a constant. This protects it from accidental changes and makes the code easier to read.

- misconception: The = sign in programming means "equals" as in maths
  reality: In programming, = is an assignment operator — it means "take the value on the right and store it in the variable on the left". To test equality, == is used.
  trigger: When students confuse assignment (=) with comparison (==)
  correction_prompt: x = 5 means "store 5 in x". x == 5 means "is x equal to 5?" These are very different. Assignment stores a value; comparison tests a condition.

- misconception: DIV is the same as normal division
  reality: DIV performs integer division — it discards the remainder and returns only the whole number result. 13 DIV 3 = 4, not 4.333.
  trigger: When students expect a decimal result from DIV
  correction_prompt: DIV discards any remainder. To get the remainder, use MOD. For a full decimal result, use ordinary division (/).

- misconception: A string and a character are interchangeable
  reality: A char holds exactly one character. A string holds zero or more characters. They are different data types and may behave differently in operations.
  trigger: When students use string and char interchangeably
  correction_prompt: char stores a single character such as 'A' or '3'. string stores text of any length, including empty strings. They are distinct data types.

