### String Manipulation

A string is anything enclosed in quote marks. Programming languages have built-in functions to manipulate strings. The functions below are in generalised pseudocode format.

Important: strings are indexed from position 0, not 1. So stringname[0] contains the first character.

To get the length of a string:

```
stringname.length
```

To get a substring:

```
stringname.substring(startingPosition, numberOfCharacters)
```

In OCR Exam Reference Language:

```
stringname.left(4)   // returns leftmost 4 characters
stringname.right(4)  // returns rightmost 4 characters
```

To convert case:

```
stringname.upper
stringname.lower
```

To find the position of a character or substring:

```
stringname.index("son")
```

Example 2 — string operations on "John Robinson":

```
myName = "John Robinson"
firstname = myName.substring(0, 3)         // "John"
surname = myName.substring(5, 7)           // "Robinson"
numChars = myName.length                   // 13
lastTwoChars = myName.substring(numChars - 2, 2)  // "on"
positionOfRob = myName.index("Rob")        // 5
```

Note: comments in pseudocode start with //.

