### Selection

Before using selection statements, it is important to understand Boolean data types and expressions — these determine which path through the program is taken.

Boolean data type:

- Boolean variables are either True or False
- Mathematical operations and comparisons (greater/less than) do not apply to Boolean values
- Boolean variables use logical operators: NOT, AND, OR

Boolean expressions:

A Boolean expression evaluates to True or False and is used to control selection statements.

Simple Boolean expression:

```
if score > 30 then
    print("Well done")
endif
```

Complex Boolean expression (uses AND, OR, NOT):

```
if (x <= 10) OR (currentCharNum > lengthOfString) then ...
```

Real-world example — estate agent search (house or flat with more than 3 bedrooms):

```
if (rooms > 3) AND ((type == "House") OR (type == "Flat")) then
    Output details
endif
```

Important: AND takes precedence over OR. The extra brackets around the OR expression are required — without them the condition would incorrectly return all houses with more than 3 bedrooms AND all flats regardless of bedroom count.

