### Writing Robust Code

Robust code will not crash due to unexpected user input.

Example — the average score algorithm from Example 3 would crash if both scores are 0. Robust version:

```
score1 = int(input("Enter score for Round 1: "))
score2 = int(input("Enter score for Round 2: "))
if (score1 == 0) AND (score2 == 0) then
    print("The average score is 0")
else
    print("The average score is ", (x + y)/2)
endif
```

Example 4 — carpet cutting algorithm:

Original (incorrect) algorithm:

```
roomLength = input("Enter room length: ")
roomWidth = input("Enter room width: ")
if roomLength > 3.9 then
    print("Carpet not wide enough")
else
    carpetLength = roomLength * 1.02
    print("Length of carpet required = ", carpetLength)
endif
```

Error: the condition checks roomLength but should check roomWidth against 3.9 (the carpet width). Also, it does not handle the case where the user may not enter the longest dimension as the length.

Corrected algorithm:

```
roomLength = input("Enter room length: ")
roomWidth = input("Enter room width: ")
if (roomLength < roomWidth) AND (roomWidth > 3.9) then
    temp = roomLength
    roomLength = roomWidth
    roomWidth = temp
endif
if roomWidth > 3.9 then
    print("Carpet not wide enough")
else
    carpetLength = roomLength * 1.02
    print("Length of carpet required = ", carpetLength)
endif
```

This ensures roomLength always holds the longer dimension before calculating, and correctly checks width against the 3.9m carpet width.

