### 7.3 – Iteration

Sections of code often need to be repeated a certain number of times, or until a condition is true or false. Three types of iterative statement are:

- for...next
- while...endwhile
- do...until

Note: not all three are available in every programming language.

---

### The for...next Loop

Use when you know exactly how many times the loop should repeat.

Example — drawing a square:

```
for n = 1 to 4
    draw line
    turn 90 degrees
next n
```

Example 5a — give a user exactly 3 attempts to enter a username:

```
accessGranted = False
for attempt = 1 to 3
    userName = input("Please enter username: ")
    if (userName != correctName) then
        userName = input("Incorrect username - please re-enter: ")
    else
        accessGranted = True
    endif
next attempt
```

Problem with this version: even if the user enters the correct username on the first attempt, they are still asked to enter it a second and third time. A while loop would be more appropriate here.

---

### The while...endwhile Loop

The condition is tested at the START of the loop. The loop body may execute zero or more times.

Used when you do not know in advance how many repetitions are needed, but need to check the condition before executing.

Example — password check:

```
while reply != "compScience"
    reply = input("Please re-enter password")
endwhile
```

Complex Boolean expressions can be used in while conditions:

```
while (NOT A > B) AND (NOT ItemFound) ...
```


