### 7.6 – Records and Files

When data items of different types need to be grouped together, a record (data structure) is used. Arrays cannot be used for this because all elements of an array must be the same data type.

Data that needs to persist between program runs must be stored in a file on disk rather than in memory.

---

### Records

A record groups related data items of different types under one structure. Each individual data item within a record is called a field.

Example — car details record in Delphi-style pseudocode:

```
type TCar = record
    registration:  string[8];
    make:          string[15];
    year:          integer;
    mileage:       integer;
    price:         integer;
end;
```

Raw data file (text):

```
RE05 HSD, Ford, 2005, 97500, 650
SW12 SDF, Vauxhall, 2012, 59650, 2500
BN64 WJR, Nissan, 2014, 39900, 18000
```

In a database, records are shown as rows in a table. Example CarTable:

```
registration | make     | year | mileage | price
AV60 HES     | Peugeot  | 2010 | 33156   | £5,500
GF56 RTE     | Toyota   | 2006 | 26875   | £8,500
FD02 YOU     | Hyundai  | 2002 | 85300   | £3,499
AD62 HGF     | Peugeot  | 2012 | 50887   | £7,649
AF63 HTE     | Peugeot  | 2013 | 45860   | £6,780
GF64 NGB     | Renault  | 2014 | 38665   | £6,199
GR11 JUL     | Renault  | 2011 | 90760   | £2,999
```


