### Handling Text Files

Text files store data as lines of text permanently on disk. Unlike records, there is no internal structure — data is read and written one line at a time.

Steps to read from a text file:

1. Tell the program where the file is
2. Open the file to read (pointer starts at the first line)
3. Read a line of text (pointer moves to the next line automatically)
4. Close the file

Steps to write to a text file:

1. Open the file to write to
2. To append, pointer must be at the end of the file (read until end of file, then write)
3. Close the file

Example 15 — writing names to a file (improved version without writing dummy value):

```
nameFile = open("names.txt")
name = input("Please enter name: ")
while name != "xxx"
    nameFile.writeLine(name)
    name = input("Please enter name: ")
endwhile
nameFile.close()
```

Note: in the first version, the dummy value "xxx" would also be written to the file. The improved version places the input statement at the end of the loop body so the condition is tested immediately after reading, before writing.

Example 16 — reading names from a file and printing them:

```
nameFile = open("names.txt")
name = nameFile.readLine()
while NOT nameFile.endOfFile()
    print(name)
    name = nameFile.readLine()
endwhile
nameFile.close()
```

In OCR Exam Reference Language, NOT nameFile.endOfFile() remains TRUE until there are no more records. The loop exits when readLine() reads the end-of-file marker.

Example 17 — reading file records into an array (assumes exactly 10 records):

```
array names[10]
nameFile = open("names.txt")
for n = 0 to 9
    names[n] = nameFile.readLine()
next n
```

