- misconception: SQL uses == to test equality in WHERE clauses
  reality: SQL uses a single = for equality in WHERE clauses, not == as used in pseudocode and Python. WHERE make = 'Peugeot' is correct SQL syntax.
  trigger: When students write == in a SQL WHERE clause
  correction_prompt: In SQL, use a single = for equality checks in WHERE clauses. The double == used in pseudocode and Python does not apply to SQL.

- misconception: You can read from a file without opening it first
  reality: A file must always be opened before reading or writing, and closed afterwards. Opening sets up the file pointer at the start of the file. Closing saves changes and frees up system resources.
  trigger: When students write file operations without open() and close() calls
  correction_prompt: Every file operation requires three steps: open the file, perform read/write operations, then close the file. Forgetting to close a file can result in data not being saved or the file being locked.

- misconception: The dummy/sentinel value is never written to a file
  reality: If the sentinel check happens after writing, the dummy value will be written. Place the input statement at the END of the while loop body so the condition is tested immediately after reading, before any write operation.
  trigger: When students write the write statement before the second input in a file-writing loop
  correction_prompt: To avoid writing the sentinel value, read input at the END of the loop so the while condition is checked right after reading. This ensures only valid data is written to the file.
